title: Our Lady of Guadalupe
artist_name: Zepeda, Sam|~|Lopez, David (American muralist and production , active 20th century)
location_description: Mural is located on Brooklyn Ave (today Cesar E. Chavez Ave) and Mednik on the exterior of the Community Development Commission. It was originally painted on a wall of one of the old Casa Maravilla housing project bungalows. The adjacent panel primarily a poem was dedicated to a young gang member killed by gang violence. When the old housing project was torn down in 1975, the Housing Authority saved these two walls and eventually placed them here.

title: Our People
artist_name: Yepes, George (American muralist and painter, 1955)|~|Carrasco, Barbara, 1955-|~|Sakai, Rod|~|Valadez, John (American muralist, born 1951)|~|Avila, Glenna Boltuch (American muralist, born 1953)|~|Callejo, Carlos (American muralist, born 1930)|~|LimoÌn, Leo
location_description: This mural is the second to occupy this same wall. In about 1974 Frank Romero covered 200 square feet with a whimsical spray can heart. In 1978 the Citywide Mural Project brought together several s to paint OUR PEOPLE (70' x 16'). Among those involved were John Valadez, Barbara Carrasco, Glenna Boltuch (Avila), Carlos Callejo, Leo LimÂ¢n, George Yepes, and Rod Sakai. In the early 1980s that mural was destroyed when new earthquake codes required Payless Shoes to add steel H-beams and make other improvements to its unreinforced masonry building.

title: Our Lady of Guadalupe
artist_name: Zepeda, Sam|~|Lopez, David (American muralist and production , active 20th century)
location_description: Mural is located on Brooklyn Ave (today Cesar E. Chavez Ave) and Mednik on the exterior of the Community Development Commission. It was originally painted on a wall of one of the old Casa Maravilla housing project bungalows. The adjacent panel primarily a poem was dedicated to a young gang member killed by gang violence. When the old housing project was torn down in 1975, the Housing Authority saved these two walls and eventually placed them here.

It was originally painted on a wall of one of the old Casa Maravilla housing project bungalows. The adjacent panel primarily a poem was dedicated to a young gang member killed by gang violence. When the old housing project was torn down in 1975, the Housing Authority saved these two walls and eventually placed them here.

title: Our People
artist_name: Yepes, George (American muralist and painter, 1955)|~|Carrasco, Barbara, 1955-|~|Sakai, Rod|~|Valadez, John (American muralist, born 1951)|~|Avila, Glenna Boltuch (American muralist, born 1953)|~|Callejo, Carlos (American muralist, born 1930)|~|LimoÌn, Leo
location_description: This mural is the second to occupy this same wall. In about 1974 Frank Romero covered 200 square feet with a whimsical spray can heart. In 1978 the Citywide Mural Project brought together several s to paint OUR PEOPLE (70' x 16'). Among those involved were John Valadez, Barbara Carrasco, Glenna Boltuch (Avila), Carlos Callejo, Leo LimÂ¢n, George Yepes, and Rod Sakai. In the early 1980s that mural was destroyed when new earthquake codes required Payless Shoes to add steel H-beams and make other improvements to its unreinforced masonry building.
